passages.text: Australia | Technology & Information Services
FY25 Result - Increased losses in the UK

The new management team used the classic playbook of rebasing earnings for the following year; however, the guidance provided does not appear conservative. The UK business is expected to incur increased losses when onboarding new lenders before they realise any benefits. In Australia, the current IT platform is becoming outdated, and more capex is needed to upgrade to a modern system architecture. Given the risks involved and expensive valuation, retain Hold.

**FY25** **result.** Revenue reached $393.6m, up 15% YoY, though this result fell short of consensus expectations by 2%. Operating EBITDA rose by 19% year-on-year to $136.7m, but was 3% below consensus on a LFL basis (after adjusting for Optima Legal interest income). PXA issued guidance for FY26, with the midpoint of the EBITDA range being 9% below consensus.

**More losses in the UK.** PEXA expects NatWest to adopt its platform for remortgaging in 1H CY26, with S&P to follow in the second half. This timeline appears achievable, as PXA indicated that the S&P platform will be available in several weeks. However, there has been limited progress with other Tier-1 lenders, which are necessary to create a network effect and drive adoption of PEXA UK. If/when additional lenders join, PXA will also incur further losses before commensurate revenue benefits are realised, likely prompting further downward revisions to our forecasts for FY26 and FY27. In addition, risks remain concerning PXA's relationships with conveyancers, who are integral to cash property transactions (no lender involved, c. 30% of all monetary transactions). Industry feedback suggests there are negative perceptions among the practitioners regarding Smoove and Optima Legal, both owned by PXA, as they also have conveyancing business. Restructuring these businesses may be required to reduce friction with the conveyancers, management distractions and ongoing losses.

**Subdued outlook for Australia.** We were quite surprised with the underwhelming guidance for the Exchange business, given more rate cuts are likely coming. That said, we also note that PXA is up against a difficult comparable period in 1H26 for Transfers (volume +9% in the pcp). The risk of inter-operability appears to have subsided but PXA needs to invest more capex in the Exchange business given that the technology is becoming outdated, needing to increase capex in FY26 and perhaps into FY27 to modernise the IT platform, borrowing from the learnings in the UK.
**Earnings revisions** We have cut our Core EBITDA forecasts by 9% in FY26E and 8% in FY27E due to increased losses in the UK.

**Roger Samuel, CFA*|Equity Analyst**
**Lucy Krimmer*|Equity Associate**

PXA is an operator of digital property settlements in Australia through the PEXA Exchange. We see continued growth in PXA, driven by 1) its clear market- leading position in the core Australian property settlement business; 2) CPI- linked annual price increases; and 3) narrow competitive landscape even under a full interoperability model in 2025.

The success of PXA's UK business provides upside to our valuation. Growth in the domestic market should offset the potential earnings drag emerging from investments in the UK and PDG (PEXA Digital Solutions).
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View
Assumptions in our Base Case include the following:

Long- term transaction volume growth of \(2.2\%\) pa. Exchange EBITDA margin of \(54\%\) in the medium to long term, constrained by regulation. UK is breakeven for the full year in FY30. Price target of \(16.20\) based on our DCF valuation.
Assumptions in our Upside Scenario include the following:

Stronger transfer and refinance activity leading to better top- line performance than our base case. Ability to raise Exchange margins beyond \(55\%\) due to a lack of regulatory scrutiny around interoperability. Better- than- expected growth in the UK, leading to market share gains. Regulatory changes in the UK moving conveyancing online creating tailwinds for PXA and others in the industry. Price target of \(21.10\) based on our DCF valuation.
Assumptions in our Downside Scenario include the following:

Lower transfer and refinance activity leading to weaker top- line performance than our base case. New competition is introduced in both Australia and the UK. UK expansion being more costly than expected, with investment continuing at peak levels for longer. Price target of \(10.50\) based on our DCF valuation.

Top Material Issue(s): 1) Foster diversity, talent, and wellbeing within the workplace. 2) Minimise operational impact on the environment and carbon footprint. 3) Ensure safety of customer data and compliance with data privacy laws.

International: Revenue grew \(15.4\%\) on a pro- forma basis, driven by strong S&P revenue and positive FX impacts. Smoove revenue grew \(23\%\) on a pro- forma basis and achieved EBITDA breakeven in 2H, Smoove maintained its \(1.5\%\) market share. Opex was \(1\%\) higher on a pro- forma basis. Implementation with NatWest is now underway, with re- mo transactions anticipated to begin in 2H FY26, followed by S&P by the end of CY 2026.

Development of UK S&P Product was completed during FY25, and the UK's first digital property transaction using the platform was successfully executed. The product will be capable of servicing \(70\%\) of UK property transactions upon launch. Further development is planned in FY26 to extend coverage to \(80\%\) .
As previously announced, NatWest is anticipated to begin transacting remortgages on the platform in the second half of FY26, followed by S&P transactions by the end of calendar year 2026.

Digital Solutions: Revenue increased \(21\%\) to \(\) 19.1\(m while Operating EBITDA was marginally negative at\) - 50.3m, though improved\) \ \(6.3m\) on FY24. As previously announced, PXA is undergoing a strategic review of the Digital Solutions business. The review may result in either a divestment or further investment in the platform. PXA have already made the decision to divest from the majority investment in Land Insight.

PEXA GroupPEXA Group is primarily an operator of digital property settlements in Australia through the PEXA Exchange and is pursuing growth opportunities in international markets. The PEXA Exchange is an Electronic Lodgment Network Operator (ELNO) facilitating electronic lodgment and settlement of property transactions through a platform connecting property market stakeholders. PEXA was established in 2010 in Melbourne, Australia.

We value PEXA based on a SOTP DCF valuation. Key assumptions underpinning our DCF valuation are DCF to FY33E with \(8.6\%\) WACC, \(4.5\%\) risk- free rate, 1.1 beta, and \(4.0\%\) terminal growth rate. Key risks include increased competition, new regulation impacting market structures, higher- than- expected investment required to grow the UK, and economic conditions affecting property markets.
